[2] Cholera, El Tor - India (Mumbai)
Date: Mon 16 Jul 2007
Source: Daily News and Analysis [edited]
<http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?NewsID=1110097>

For the 1st time this monsoon [2007], the Brihanmumbai Municipal
Corporation (BMC) hospitals have shifted at least 15 patients from
different hospitals to one civic hospital citing "medical reasons".
BMC's executive health officer Jairaj Thanekar admitted that it is El
Tor cholera, but not "classic cholera". His comment was in response
to a query when this paper asked why there is a sudden need to
isolate some patients. (The El Tor form tends to be milder in nature,
while the classic is more often fatal.)
The 15 patients, most of who are from Antop Hills, were moved to
Kasturba Gandhi Hospital at Mahalaxmi from the KEM (King Edward
Memorial), Nair, and Sion hospitals over the last 7 days. The
decision to isolate 15 patients has created a panic though the civic
authorities vehemently denied any outbreak of monsoon-related
diseases.
The 15 patients are now being monitored in Kasturba Hospital, which
has a special ward for diarrhea cases. Interestingly, the BMC termed
the disease "extreme gastroenteritis" or extreme "diarrhea".
"As of now, we have been told there are only cases of gastroenteritis
and diarrhea, but not cholera," added Dr Suhas Ranade, Assistant
Director, Directorate of Health Services (DHS).
Thanekar also added that 70 percent of the "mild cholera patients"
have already been discharged. "These are not cases of classic cholera
so there is nothing to panic," he added. "Figures are not with me."
[Byline: Sumitra Deb Roy]
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The flagellar (H) antigens of _Vibrio cholerae_ are shared with many
water vibrios and therefore are of no use in distinguishing strains
causing epidemic cholera. The O (somatic) antigens, however, do
distinguish strains of _V. cholerae_ into 139 known serotypes. Almost
all of these strains of _V. cholerae_ are nonvirulent. Until the
emergence of the Bengal strain (which is "non-O1"), a single
serotype, designated O1, has been responsible for epidemic cholera.
However, there are 3 distinct O1 biotypes, named Ogawa, Inaba, and
Hikojima, each of which may display the "classical" or El Tor
phenotype.
A map of the southern city island of Mumbai (Bombay) can be seen at
<http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/maharashtra/mumbai-map.htm>. The
city's location on the western coast of India can be seen at
<http://www.lonelyplanet.com/mapshells/indian_subcontinent/india/india.htm>.
- Mod.LL]
