[3] Cholera, diarrhea - Nepal (Katmandu)
Date: Wed 18 Jul 2006
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, IRIN (UN Integrated Regional
Information Networks) report [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/505c6b25abdf174dc785827be2deb3ee.htm>

Health bodies and UN agencies in Nepal have taken emergency measures
in the capital, Katmandu, and elsewhere to control a cholera outbreak
1st reported last week [9-15 Jul 2007].
Diarrheal diseases are endemic in the country but this monsoon season
[2007] Katmandu had a record 223 cases of cholera, according to the
Epidemiology and Disease Control Division (EPCD) of the Department of
Health.
Acute gastroenteritis, also known as acute watery diarrhea, has
already claimed 5 lives, and there are over 3700 cases, the EPCD, a
government agency charged with managing outbreaks and public health
emergencies, said. "The problem became worse this year [2007] due to
severe water pollution," Manas Kumar Banerjee, director of EPCD, told
IRIN on 18 Jul 2007. Banerjee said water quality in Katmandu was very
low and much of the drinking water was polluted.
In April 2007, 28 percent of the city's drinking water was unsafe to
drink. By July 2007, it had worsened to a dangerously high level of
72 percent.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[How many of the acute watery diarrhea cases are also cholera is not
clear. Katmandu (KTM) can be found on the map at
<http://ncthakur.itgo.com/map04.htm>. - Mod.LL]
